</li><li id="tree_64190120" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64190120" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64190120" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64190120" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64190120" name="comment_link_64190120" href="//apple.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206088&amp;cid=64190120" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64190120)" >Re:Buh bye</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64190120" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64190120); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Njovich">Njovich</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Njovich">( 553857 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64190120">		
		on Friday January 26, 2024 @02:05PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//apple.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206088&amp;cid=64190120">#64190120</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64190120"><p>Your comment paints an intriguing, albeit extreme, scenario. Let's unpack what it would really mean for Apple to 'take their ball and go home' from Europe. First off, consider the contractual obligations. Apple would need to settle accounts with suppliers, carriers, consumers, and businesses. Would their European subsidiaries file for bankruptcy, surrendering assets and intellectual property? It's possible that European entities could then acquire the Apple brand in the region through government-led auctions.</p><p>The App Store alone poses a significant challenge. Ceasing its operations in Europe could trigger a cascade of lawsuits from consumers seeking refunds for their premium devices, now deprived of essential services. Moreover, app developers, especially major U.S.-based ones, would likely sue for lost revenue, aggravated by Apple's contractual commitments like Google's default browser status in Europe.</p><p>These legal battles wouldn't be confined to Europe. Apple, as a publicly traded company, would face immediate legal challenges in the U.S., particularly from investors concerned about a sudden 25% drop in revenue. This is not just about market dynamics; it's a potential corporate governance crisis.</p><p>Employment is another critical angle. With approximately 22,000 employees in Europe, Apple can't simply vanish without addressing labor laws, severance packages, and potential lawsuits. This extends beyond retail stores; it encompasses a complex network of operational, legal, and financial obligations across multiple countries.</p><p>Finally, consider the response from governments and competitors. Apple withdrawing from such a lucrative market would likely be seen as a strategic blunder, one that competitors (Asians, American and Europeans alike) would eagerly exploit. It's not just about a corporate tit-for-tat; it's about the broader implications for market dynamics, employment, and technological presence in Europe.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64190120">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64190120" class="btn link" href="//apple.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206088&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64190120" onclick="D2.replyTo(64190120); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//apple.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206088&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64189980" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64189980)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
